org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Simulation.name: The Case of Palmyra
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Simulation.introduction:
Violence is escalating once again the country of Siwa, a poor country torn by a decade-long rebellion. International humanitarian assistance groups are urging the United Nations to explore ways to halt the conflict and establish security in the region. These organizations are calling on the UN to provide peacekeeping forces to increase security and to provide assistance to the large numbers of refugees through the offices of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees.

In addition, the regional organization, NESO (North East States Organization), composed of all states in the region, is exerting political and economic pressure on the parties to stop the fighting and discuss peace.

To explore options for bringing an end to the violence and establish security in the region, a group of outside organizations has convened a meeting with all parties affected by the conflict to begin a process that will lead to peace.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Simulation.learningObjvs: To provide the participants with insights into some of the skills and approaches that can lead to successful negotiation and mediation. These include: accurately analyzing parties' positions and interests; communication of different views to others; eliciting new ideas and differentiating between positions and interests; promoting areas of common agreement; adjusting positions without sacrificing one's interests; and helping make an agreement that will last and can be implemented by all sides.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Simulation.plannedPlayIdeas:
There are five actors in this simulation. All are required with the possible exception of the NESO mediator.

There are 3 significant parts to this simulation.
1. The actors will have an initial meeting in which the parties will lay out their positions and do some initial discussion.
2. This will be followed by consultations during which each of the representatives will consult with their principals and the two mediators will meet to consider their next steps.
3. The second meeting of the parties will lead to identification of the basic principles of a peace agreement and a commitment on the part of the parties to meet again to work out the specific elements.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Simulation.aarStarterText:
During the reflection phase, the actors have been asked to respond to the following questions and be prepared to discuss them:
  1. What was the conflict really about? What were the interests of the two governments and the PLM?
  2. Why were the parties ready to negotiate?
  3. What seemed to make the difference in the negotiations -- when did things begin moving toward an agreement?
  4. What elements of the agreement make you think this peace will last?
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Simulation.creator: USIP

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.name: Representative of the Government of Nizwa
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.public__description:
Although Nizwa initially supported the PLM, the war has had devastating consequences. Its military forces are weak and it has effectively lost control over its Jebela region. It is important that the civil war between the PLM and Siwa be settled so that Nizwa can focus its attention on economic development. This war is not of Nizwa's making and it has called for UN peacekeepers to stop the fighting and for peace negotiations between the PLM and Siwa begin immediately.

The refugee situation has created instability in the Jebela region, and the country's resources are overwhelmed by their needs. You have called for intervention by the UN High Commissioner for Refugees to provide assistance, something it is unwilling to do because of the active fighting in that region.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.semi__public__description: The continuing war has put a strain on Nizwan resources and caused unrest along the border because of the refugees. Crime has increased, agricultural land has been destroyed, and many Nizwa citizens have been killed in the border area. Rebels are strip mining and harvesting timber, actions that are destroying or eroding arable land and polluting rivers. The economic consequences have been dire.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.private__description:
Initially the government of Nizwa supported the PLM by providing funding and access to bases in the Jebela region. However, as the war spread and fighting became increasingly brutal, the government ended its support. This has been controversial within the country -- support for the PLM increases within Nizwa the farther from Jebela one goes. Nizwans living in the region are strongly opposed to the civil war while those in the east of the country support it.

However, Nizwa's military forces are so weak that it can no longer control Jebela and some within the government is concerned what would happen if the PLM forces abandoned their claims on Palmyra and instead sought to overthrow the Nizwa government.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.name: Representative of the Palmyra Liberation Movement (PLM)
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.public__description: The PLM has no wish to stop fighting unless the status quo is changed. There can be no peacekeeping forces without an agreement to discuss independence for Palmya. If the PLM is to lay down arms, it wants assurances that the Nizwan refugees will be allowed to return to Palmyra before a referendum on Palmyra independence is held. You also want to ensure that the PLM is allowed to become a legitimate political party in Siwa prior to the referendum.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.semi__public__description: Refugee camps are a prime area for recruitment into the PLM forces, so it is important that you retain access to them.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.private__description: PLM leadership, including yourself, has little incentive to make peace without independence because you are making considerable money for the liberation movement as well as for yourselves through your control of the gems in Jebela. In addition, there has been discussion in the international community about human rights violations that have taken place during the decade-long civil war, and this places PLM leaders at risk of prosecution.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.name: United Nations Mediator
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.public__description:
Your immediate objectives are for a stop to the killing and fighting and establish a buffer zone, for the two sides to agree to a peacekeeping force that will separate the combatants, and for negotiations for a permanent peace to begin.

Your long term objective is for the rebels to be disarmed and returned to civilian life in Palmyra.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.semi__public__description: There is considerable political sentiment in the Security Council against sending UN peacekeeping forces without a similar commitment by NESO. The UN is willing to provide leadership and support, but does not want its peacekeepers to be the only forces in the Nizwan/Palmyran conflict.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.private__description: Ideally, you would like to see the PLM leaders identified as the worst perpetrators of war crimes to be tried and punished; you would not, however, hold up a peace or disengagement agreement for that reason. In addition, to get an agreement for a UN presence it will be necessary to secure the agreement of the Siwan government, some of whom are themselves accused of war crimes.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.name: Representative of North East States Organization (NESO)
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.public__description:
Your organization represents the states in this part of the world, including both Nizwa and Siwa. NESO wants to stop the fighting and halt the economic and environmental destruction that is having a ripple effect throughout the region.
You want a durable peace, but strongly oppose independence for Palmyra because many of the member states have similar situations where minorities have aspirations of independence.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.semi__public__description: If necessary, to move the parties toward a peace agreement, many members of NESO are willing to exert economic pressure through cutting off trade or economic sanctions, or through the offer of incentives such as increased trade and economic aid and investment.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.private__description: Members of NESO are reluctant to provide peacekeeping forces unless the UN sends peacekeepers as well. They do not have funds or the know-how to carry out a long-term peacekeeping role.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.name: Representative of the Government of Siwa
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.public__description:
Siwa has been immersed in a civil war for the past 10 years. The area in which most of the fighting has taken place is the territory of Palmyra.

Many of the PLM rebels, although fighting for Palmyran independence, have bases across the border in Nizwa, especially in the mountains around the town of Jebela. Siwa wants the PLM forced out of the Jebela region so they can no longer finance their revolt or use the area as a safe haven between attacks inside Siwa.

Siwa is calling for peacekeeping forces to be deployed immediately to create a barrier between the rebel bases and Siwa. It also wants PLM leadership handed over to face charges of treason and murder.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.semi__public__description:
Peacekeeping forces will allow Siwa to consolidate control over Palmyra by keeping the rebels at bay. This is important because the fighting is a major drain on the country's resources, and because there have been calls from the political opposition for a negotiated peace.

The refugee camps inside the Nizwa border are filled with Nizwans who fled from the fighting in Palmyra. The peacekeeping forces would help close the border between the two countries so that the refugees could not return to Palmyra. This is important to the Siwans living there who at the outset of the war were the minority culture there, but who now make up the majority.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.Actor.private__description: The Siwan army has been accused of committing atrocities against the civilian population during its fight against the rebels. The government is aware of several such instances but has publicly and vehemently denied that any atrocities have taken place. One of the army generals who appears to have been involved is the brother of the Siwan president. Consequently, Siwa refuses to entertain any discussion in these talks of atrocities.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Introduction
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: The actors will read the backgrounder on the Palmyra conflict as well as the public information about each actor. In addition, each representative has instructions that they will read to guide their interaction in the first meeting.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: First meeting in Smyrna
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: All actors will participate in a chat in which the two governments and the PLM present their perspectives with the assistance of the two mediators.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Consultation
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: The representatives will consult with their governments, the two mediators will meet, and the representatives of Nizwa and of Siwa will meet.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Second meeting in Smyrna
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: The three representatives will meet with the two mediators and will discuss the basic principles of a peace agreement.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Reflection
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: During this phase the actors reflect on what they learned during the simulation.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.name: Debriefing
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.SimulationPhase.notes: This is a debriefing phase in which the actors will use the AAR to discuss what they have learned.

An 'after action report' (AAR) is a document written after an event describing what happened and what the lessons learned were. Adding this section to a simulation adds a page showing the after action report that the instructor has written. This is generally considered the essential final step of a simulation: to provide feedback to the players on how they have done, and give them thoughts to reflect upon.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.CustomizeableSe.bigString:
For ten years, Siwa, a relatively poor country with a mixed population of majority Siwans and minority Nizwans, has confronted rebellion in the territory of Palmyra, a province that borders the country of Nizwa and where ethnic Nizwans are the majority.

The violence has been extreme. Initially, the rebellion began as a political movement for greater autonomy for the Nizwan minority in Siwa, led by the Palmyra Liberation Movement (PLM). There were demands
for greater freedom of religion (Siwans are animist, Nizwans Buddhist) as well as the use of the Nizwan language in schools and the conduct of official business in the province of Palmyra.

Siwans who live in Palmyra strongly opposed greater Nizwan autonomy. When the government attempted to clamp down on the PLM, considerable violence broke out. The government charged that the violence was instigated by Nizwans. The Nizwans claim that the government purposely initiated the violence to have an excuse to use force to halt the autonomy movement. Groups of armed men began to challenge the government forces and widespread violence erupted into armed rebellion in Palmyra.

In the years of fighting since, there have been charges of atrocities on both sides. In addition, thousands have been made homeless. Nizwan refugees have formed camps along the border in neighboring Nizwa. Displaced Siwans have relocated into homes abandoned by those Nizwan refugees.

Most of the soldiers in the rebel movement are based in the Jebela Mountains inside Nizwa along the border. They often cross over into Siwa on raids and then escape back into the mountains.

In order to continue financing their rebellion and secure armaments, the rebels have taken to illegal mining of the gems in the Jebela region, as well as plundering border areas of Siwa.

For many years the Nizwa government ignored the growing numbers of rebels inside its borders. It had provided some support for the initial political movement, but as opposition to Siwan authority became increasingly violent, the Nizwa regime has disavowed any support for the rebels. Nizwa is also concerned that the Siwa government may attack Nizwa under the pretext of pursuing the rebels. Nizwa has many fewer men and women under arms than Siwa and does not want to provoke the Siwans unnecessarily. On the other hand, many Nizwans are sympathetic to the rebels so the government provides rhetorical support if not actual financial and military support. However, the Nizwa government does support the rebel contention that Palmyra has historically been settled by Nizwans and strongly opposes any effort by Siwans to push out the Nizwans and re-settle the area with Siwans.

Siwa, on the other hand, believes that the violence is nothing but an unlawful campaign of terror and rebellion against a legitimate regime and law-abiding citizens. The Siwan Government notes that the territory in question has been sovereign Siwa territory for centuries and has insisted that the international community should not try to interfere with Siwa's domestic matters as Siwa tries to defend itself from attack from inside and outside its borders.

With the growing violence and the large numbers of refugees, many international humanitarian assistance groups have urged the United Nations to provide peacekeeping forces to help provide security in the border area as well as provide assistance to the civilians through the offices of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees. In addition, the regional organization, NESO (North East States Organization), made up of all states in the region is putting political and economic pressure on the parties to stop the fighting and discuss peace.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.CustomizeableSe.bigString:
To: Representative of the Government of Nizwa
From: Ministry of Foreign Affairs
Re: Initial Instructions Concerning Negotiations in Smyrna

These negotiations are important to the Government of Nizwa because of the instability the ongoing civil war poses to our nation.

You are to forcefully lay out our position:
  1. We seek a peaceful resolution of the conflict that began within Siwa.
  2. We demand that the PLM forces leave its territory
  3. We request that the UN High Commissioner on Refugees assist the refugees currently living in camps in the Jebela region to return to their former homes in Palmyra.
  4. We request the UN and NESO to introduce peacekeeping forces to guard the border between Siwa and Nizwa.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.CustomizeableSe.bigString:
To:  Representative of the Government of Siwa
From:  Ministry of Foreign Affairs
Re:  Negotiations in Smyrna

CONFIDENTIAL

These negotiations are critical to Siwa's resolution of the civil war. You are to forcefully state this government's positions:
  1. The civil war must end through the surrender of the PLM and its forces.
  2. A peacekeeping force must be brought in to protect the border of Siwa along the Jebela region so that the PLM rebels and the Naziwan refugees are not able to re-enter Siwa.
  3. We are prepared to enter Naziwa to protect our interests, and while there is no interest on the part of Siwa in extending this conflict to that nation, we are prepared to occupy the Jebela region for as long as necessary to prevent it from remaining a safe haven for belligerent forces.
org.usip.osp.baseobjects.CustomizeableSe.description: To the Representative of the Government of Siwa

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.CustomizeableSe.bigString:
To:  Representative of PLM
From: Revolutionary Command
Re: Negotiations in Smyrna

CONFIDENTIAL

This is a pivotal time in our decade-long war of liberation. You are to forcefully present the position of the PLM as it begins these negotiations:
  1. We demand independence of the Palmyra region from Siwa.
  2. We demand the return of Nizwan refugees from the Jebela region of Nizwa to their homes in Palmyra.
  3. We are willing to leave forces in the Jebela region to help maintain order in the area.
  4. We oppose introduction of outside military forces in the region from either the UN or NESO.
Although you should not reveal this, we are interested in maintaining control over the gem mines in Jebela region because of the important sources of revenue they represent. This is our motivation for point 3 of our position.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.CustomizeableSe.bigString:
To:  Representative of NESO
From:  NESO Headquarters
Re:  Negotiations in Smyrna

CONFIDENTIAL

You should ally yourself with the UN mediator's efforts to understand what the conflict is about and to understand the sources of power and leverage in the conflict. The other representatives will begin with their official positions, but they will offer clues that will help you and the UN mediator later on as you discuss how to conduct the second meeting.

You are to communicate to the others NESO's grave concern with the destabilizing effects the prolonged civil war over Palmyra Province has had in the region. The humanitarian, environmental and political crises that this has created cannot continue. As members of NESO, we pledge our support to the governments of Siwa and Nizwa in finding a solution.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.CustomizeableSe.bigString:
To:  Representative of Nizwa
From:  Minister of Foreign Affairs
Re:  Important news from NESO meetings

CONFIDENTIAL

As you know, Heads of States that are members of NESO have been meeting. Our President and the President of Siwa have spoken informally about the negotiations currently taking place in Smyrna. They have agreed that it is in both of the countries' interests for the civil war to end and the PLM to be disarmed. Because significant funding for the rebellion comes from PLM's sale of Jebela gems, they have agreed to issue a joint call for the international community to treat the gems under the parameters of the Kimberley Process Certification System (http://www.diamondfacts.org/conflict/index.html).

We believe that this will be a significant blow to PLM. It should lead to its recognition that it must come to a political settlement of the long civil war. Provided that this happens, and that it results in the rebel forces and refugee camps being relocated from the Jebela region, you are authorized to negotiate settlement of those issues and any others that may arise.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.CustomizeableSe.bigString:
To:  Representative of PLM
From:  Revolutionary Command
Re:  Developments from NESO meetings

CONFIDENTIAL

We have received word that the Presidents of Siwa and Nizwa have spoken informally during a meeting of all Heads of State that are members of NESO. They have agreed that it is in both of the countries' interests for the rebellion to end and the PLM to be disarmed. They have agreed to call on the international community to prevent the sale of gems from Jebela and thereby cut off our funding for the civil war. The Presidents have agreed to ask that the gems be treated under the parameters of the Kimberley Process Certification System (http://www.diamondfacts.org/conflict/index.html).

This is a serious blow to the PLM. If our revenues from sale of gems were reduced to even 70% of their current level, we will not be able to continue the civil war.  This is very likely to happen now that the two governments are united on this. Of course, you should not admit that the armed conflict will likely end or that the gems are our primary source of funding.

However, the goals of PLM must now shift to a political objective of creating the autonomous region of Palmyra (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autonomous_area). While this is much less than independence, it would give some measure of autonomy to the Province.

It is important that the refugees now living in Jebela be allowed to return to Palmyra so that ethnic Nizwans are a majority population in Palmyra as they were when the civil war began.

It is also critical that there be no legal action taken against leaders of PLM by either the Siwan or international community. Amnesty must be part of any agreement.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.CustomizeableSe.bigString:
To:  UN Mediator
From:  UN Headquarters
Re:  Developments from NESO

CONFIDENTIAL

The Presidents of Siwa and Nizwa have jointly called on the international community to prevent the sale of gems from Jebela. This apparently arose out of informal conversations that the two had during meetings of Heads of States that are members of NESO.

This is significant because if gem sales can be disrupted, the PLM will not have enough funds to continue its rebellion. The Presidents have agreed to ask that the gems be treated under the parameters of the Kimberley Process Certification System (http://www.diamondfacts.org/conflict/index.html).

This is likely a game changer. If the PLM's revenues from sale of gems is significantly reduced, it will not be able to continue the civil war. The best it can expect is a political resolution, perhaps through Siwa's granting of autonomous status for Palmyra Province (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autonomous_area). This would be less than independence, which may make this acceptable to Siwa.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.CustomizeableSe.bigString:
To:  Representative of NESO
From:  NESO Headquarters
Re:  Developments from NESO Heads of State Meetings

CONFIDENTIAL

The Presidents of Siwa and Nizwa have jointly called on the international community to prevent the sale of gems from Jebela. This arose out of informal conversations that the two had during meetings of Heads of States that are members of NESO.

This is significant because if gem sales can be disrupted, the PLM will not have enough funds to continue its rebellion. The Presidents have agreed to ask that the gems be treated under the parameters of the Kimberley Process Certification System (http://www.diamondfacts.org/conflict/index.html).

This is likely a game changer. If the PLM's revenues from sale of gems is significantly reduced, it will not be able to continue the civil war. The best it can expect is a political resolution, perhaps through Siwa's granting of autonomous status for Palmyra Province (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autonomous_area). This would be less than independence, which may make this acceptable to Siwa.

Two remaining sticking points are likely to be the return of Nizwan refugees now in camps in Jebela to their homes in Palmyra, and the threat of prosecution of the leaders of PLM by Siwa or the international community.

If this civil war can be ended, it will substantially reduce tensions in the NESO region. You should do what you can to help the UN Mediator to negotiate a conclusion. NESO remains willing to send peacekeeping forces provided that the UN does so as well.

This document can be any time in nature, a report, a memorandum of understanding, etc. After adding a document to be written by a player, it will probably be necessary to add it as a document that can be read.

org.usip.osp.baseobjects.CustomizeableSe.bigString:
Please respond to the following questions and be prepared to discuss them with the others in the simulation:
  1. What was the conflict really about? What were the interests of the two governments and the PLM?
  2. Why were the parties ready to negotiate?
  3. What seemed to make the difference in the negotiations -- when did things begin moving toward an agreement?
  4. What elements of the agreement make you think this peace will last?
